 Raju proves a point
A STAFF REPORTER Special Olympics medal winners (from left) Chinmoy Middya, Sagarika Hazra, Manasi Samanta and Raju Ghosh on arrival at the Howrah station on Sunday. Sheik Sahib, Ranjan Dutta and Santu Negal were the other Bengal participants who won medals in the summer meet which concluded in Shanghai on Thursday. A Telegraph picture Calcutta: He admires Sourav Ganguly and dreams of leading the country  in cricket for differently abled. Already the skipper of Bengal team for differently abled, Raju Ghosh on Sunday returned from Shanghai with a bronze medal. Included as a recognised sport in 2007 Special Olympics World Summer Games (October 2-11), cricket earned India abronze medal in the Shanghai meet. The 25-year-old from Konnagar picked up cricket after Prochesta  an NGO  spotted his talent way back in 1997. He (Raju) was very aggressive from his childhood and picked up with the sport very fast, an official of the NGO said. Raju, who is unable to speak, went on to become a left-handed batsman and right-arm medium fast bowler. The allrounders first claim to fame came in 2006 when he was adjudged Man of the Tournament in a five-nation meet in Mumbai. Sunil Gavaskar and Wasim Akram handed him an autographed bat as a mark of his performance, the official said, adding some financial help from the government will be a big help for the talented cricketer. 
